class Solution {
public:
    int minOperations(int n) {
        int count = 0;
        while (n != 0) {
            n = abs(n) & (n - 1);
            count++;
        }
        return count;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: This solution uses bitwise operations to find the number of trailing zeros in the binary representation of n, which is equivalent to the minimum number of operations required to make n equal to 0. The while loop continues until n becomes 0, and the count of operations is incremented each time. The bitwise operation (n - 1) & n clears the least significant bit of n if it is 1, effectively removing the last power of 2 from n.

